  "text": "## Leader Election Patterns Comparison\n\n### Kubernetes: Lease-Based Leader Election\n\n**Architecture:**\nKubernetes uses a distributed lease-based leader election mechanism that relies on the Kubernetes API server and Lease objects in the coordination API. This is implemented in `k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection`.\n\n**Key Components:**\n\n1. **LeaderElector** (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/leaderelection.go): The main client-side component that orchestrates leader election\n   - `Run()`: Starts the election loop, calling `acquire()` to get leadership, then `renew()` to maintain it\n   - `acquire(ctx)`: Loops attempting to acquire the lease through `tryAcquireOrRenew()` with RetryPeriod delays\n   - `renew(ctx)`: Continuously renews the lease with a RenewDeadline timeout; if renewal fails, stops leading\n   - `tryAcquireOrRenew()`: Core logic that checks if the lease is valid and updates the Lease object\n\n2. **ResourceLock Interface** (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/interface.go): Abstraction for different lock backends\n   - `Interface` defines Get(), Create(), Update() operations\n   - `LeaderElectionRecord` contains: HolderIdentity, LeaseDurationSeconds, AcquireTime, RenewTime, LeaderTransitions\n\n3. **LeaseLock** (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/leaselock.go): Implements the Interface using Kubernetes Lease API\n   - Uses `coordinationv1.Lease` objects stored in etcd\n   - `Get()`: Retrieves the current lease from the API server\n   - `Update()`: Updates the RenewTime and holder identity in the lease spec\n\n4. **LeaseCandidate** (staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/leasecandidate.go): Advanced coordinated leader election using LeaseCandidate objects for version-based leader selection\n\n**Failover Mechanism:**\n- **Timeout-based detection**: Leaders continuously renew their lease before RenewDeadline expires\n- **LeaseDuration**: Non-leaders must wait for this duration without observing an update before attempting to acquire\n- **Leader transitions**: When a leader can't renew before RenewDeadline, the lease becomes stale\n- **Acquisition**: Any non-leader can then update the lease and become the new leader\n- **Re-election**: Tracked via LeaderTransitions counter; leader change triggers OnNewLeader callbacks\n- **Integration** (pkg/controlplane/controller/leaderelection/leaderelection_controller.go): Kubernetes control plane components use this for HA setup\n\n---\n\n### etcd: Raft-Based Leader Election\n\n**Architecture:**\netcd uses the Raft consensus algorithm for distributed leader election, implemented in the go.etcd.io/raft/v3 library. The server integration is in `server/etcdserver`.\n\n**Key Components:**\n\n1. **raftNode** (server/etcdserver/raft.go): Wrapper around the Raft state machine\n   - `start(rh *raftReadyHandler)`: Launches the raft node's event loop\n   - Processes `raft.Ready()` messages containing RaftState changes\n   - Detects leader changes via `rd.SoftState.Lead` (peer ID of current leader)\n   - Metrics: leaderChanges counter, hasLeader flag, isLeader flag track leadership transitions\n\n2. **raftReadyHandler** (server/etcdserver/server.go): Interface for raft state machine to notify EtcdServer\n   - `getLead()`: Returns current leader ID from atomic variable\n   - `updateLead(lead uint64)`: Sets the leader ID when Raft reports a change\n   - `updateLeadership(newLeader bool)`: Called when leadership status changes\n\n3. **EtcdServer** (server/etcdserver/server.go): Integrates Raft with the etcd server\n   - `lead` (atomic.Uint64): Atomic variable storing the current leader's member ID\n   - `leaderChanged`: Notifier channel that broadcasts when leader changes\n   - `isLeader()`: Checks if `MemberID() == Lead()`\n   - `Leader()`: Returns current leader as types.ID\n   - `LeaderChangedNotify()`: Returns channel for monitoring leadership changes\n\n**Failover Mechanism:**\n- **Heartbeat detection**: Leader sends periodic heartbeat messages to followers\n- **Election trigger**: When followers don't receive heartbeats within an election timeout, they become candidates\n- **Raft election**: Candidates request votes from other peers; first to get majority becomes leader\n- **State machine update**: When Raft detects a new leader (rd.SoftState.Lead != previous), it calls `updateLeadership(newLeader=true)`\n- **Notification**: `leaderChanged.Notify()` broadcasts to all listeners (e.g., linearizable read handlers)\n- **Leadership actions** (updateLeadership callback):\n  - On becoming leader: Record election time (`leadElectedTime`), resume compactor\n  - On losing leadership: Pause compactor, demote lessor\n  - Logs leadership status to stats\n- **Consensus guarantee**: Raft ensures only one leader per term, preventing split-brain scenarios\n\n---\n\n### Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes (Lease-Based) | etcd (Raft-Based) |\n|--------|--------------------------|-------------------|\n| **Election Mechanism** | Optimistic concurrency control via API server updates | Consensus algorithm with voting |\n| **Failover Detection** | Timeout-based (LeaseDuration) | Heartbeat timeout + election |\n| **Implementation** | Client-side, decoupled from data layer | Integrated with consensus for consistency |\n| **Consistency** | Best-effort, clock-dependent | Strong, term-based ordering |\n| **State Storage** | Kubernetes Lease API objects | Raft state machine, persistent log |\n| **Notification** | LeaderCallbacks (OnStartedLeading, OnStoppedLeading) | leaderChanged channel, LeaderChangedNotify() |\n| **Guarantee** | No fencing; two leaders possible during clock skew | No split-brain; Raft consensus prevents dual leaders |\n"
}

